[Our thanks to Sabine for this report.

Being exposed to a carcass in floodwater sounds strange, but dumping a carcass into a flooded river is a convenient way used by the careless to get rid of it. One of my students once told me that his dad, a dairy farmer, once hauled a dead cow out of the Red River and skinned it. It didn't come free, as he subsequently lost some 8 cows grazing that riverside field to anthrax; presumably, they visited the carcass and the spilt blood. I doubt whether this Romanian woman could have similarly dragged a carcass out of their flooded river. It was probably done by a neighbour, which would imply that others would have been exposed.

The fellow's story is typical of slaughtering and butchering a sick animal. To be "cut by a bone" while butchering is uncommon, unless the animal had a broken limb or some other trauma. Or maybe he was just careless, cut himself, and blamed the cow.

Both cases have yet to be confirmed.

For a map of Romania, go to http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/europe/romania_pol96.jpg, where Olt is on the south-central border with Bulgaria. The woman's village Colonesti is at http://www.fallingrain.com/world/RO/00/Colonesti2.html, and her hospital in Pitesti, Arges county, is at http://www.fallingrain.com/world/RO/03/Pitesti.html. The man's village, Dobrossloveni, is at http://www.fallingrain.com/world/RO/00/Dobrosloveni.html, and Caracal, his hospital, is nearby at http://www.fallingrain.com/world/RO/00/Caracal2.html. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2679895,122.]
